# Introduction (section=D1)
It’s 6pm on Friday evening and I’m standing with Harry Stone in the Gallery of Living Art across from Washington Square park, where they’ve just opened the doors on an exhibition of paintings by local police officers, and people are starting to trickle in.  Harry’s my new deputy sergeant, and we’ve only been partnered for a couple of weeks, but I don’t think he’s ever stepped foot in an art gallery before. He’s smart enough to know that he’s supposed to like my work.
“It looks just like him”, he says.
I wince.  It’s a painting of the old man who owned the shoe store outside of the 6th precinct where we work. His face looks as thin as a vagabond’s, lined and crumpled like a discarded tobacco wrapper. That much I got right.  But his eyes haunt me. How do you capture the spirit of a guy who came to America without a penny to his name, managed to survive a financial crisis that wiped out half the city, and then was beaten to death by some maniac who was having a bad day. I can barely look at it without feeling sick.
“Lieutenant Malcolm Lockwood?” someone whispers behind me, catching me off guard.
It’s too late to pretend I wasn’t spooked, so I just flip my fedora back on my head and turn casually.  It’s Archie Babin, a beat cop I know from my patrolman days.  A friend. Well, sort of.
“Long time no see, Archie.”  He looks embarrassed to be caught in a place like this.  He’s the size of a large bear and he sticks out among the starving artists.
His hat’s already in his hand, and I can see right away this is personal.  “I need favour, Malcolm.”  Right to the point. He’s not messing around.
“It’s my little brother, sir.  He’s mixed up in something, and he won’t talk to me.”
“What do you expect me to do about it, Archie?”
“I need you to talk to him, sir, find out what‘s going on.  Talk some sense into him.”
I want to ask Archie how that’s supposed to work, but what’s the point.  I look over at Harry to see what he thinks, and he’s already got his notepad out.  Good kid. “Ok, Archie, what’s his name and where can I find him?”
“Sam. Sam Babin.  He’s my little brother.  He’s a PI up in Bloomingdale.  As for where you can find him, he’s a Jazz nut. Spends most of his days in a joint called the Cosy Cat or Cozy Cave, or, something like that, up on Broadway.”
Harry gives me a look and shrugs.  I give Archie a reassuring pat on the back. “Ok, Archie, we’ll see what we can do.”  Anything to get me out of here.

