# 1-3018: 10 Downing Street Apartments – doorman
It turns out that Harry knows the doorman at 10 Downing Street Apartments.
“Hiya Danny! How’s life treating you?” Harry booms, while grabbing Danny’s hand and pumping wildly. The Sergeant’s smile is warm enough to heat coffee. “Let me introduce my new lieutenant – Malcolm Lockwood.”  Then he turns to me: “Lieutenant, Danny here’s kind of like a knight in shining armour. He takes care of his flock so the wolves don’t get ‘em.” I almost want to explain to Harry the concept of a mixed metaphor, but we don’t have the time.
Danny looks like he might have been a dapper chap once – before his love affair with German beer and Italian pasta. We give him a description of Sam Babin and ask if he’s seen him.
“Ya, I know that guy,” Danny replies in a thick Russian accent. “Started showing up a month ago. Always he asks to see Miss Ayala. She never lets him up to her place. Instead, she comes here to the lobby where I can keep watch. And always she takes her two friends along with her – Miss Blaak and Miss Uvarova. Since a month ago, they talk with him maybe once a week. The first time he came here, I saw Miss Ayala give him a picture of someone, but I could not see face. And Miss Ayala is always giving him a little folded piece of paper when they meet.  Maybe a bank check or a note or something like that. I don’t know if that’s important.  Do you think it could be?”
“Could be” I say, nodding. “You don’t happen to know if she uses a bank around here, do you, Danny?”
He thinks for a second.“There’s a bank on Broadway”, says Danny, “but I think Mrs. Ayala uses the one downtown, on Broom street.”
“Oh and one more thing officer,” Danny lifts his huge hand and points across the street. “Sometimes, they go to Dante’s to talk. They just went over a little while ago.”
“You saw them tonight?” I give Harry a quick glance.
“Yes sir. All three walked over to Dante’s around 7pm. I assume they are still there.” Looks like we caught a break.
“Keep up the good work, Danny,” Harry says, shaking his hand.
As Danny walks us out the front door an old lady across Downing street is leaning outside of her balcony trying to get his attention.  “Danny, I told you those harlots are up to no good! They’re going to get you locked up one of these days.  Stay away from harlots!”
“She’s always looking out for me,” he says, waving her off with a smile.
